task.summary: Commit 6: Fixed RSS framework. Buggy as hell due to a reference to another R.java file in the config, rather than the Allnone app's R.java. Overlap from poor implementation of copy-pasted code.

Commit 7: decided to redo HTTP methods, mainly because I didn't like the way in which I was doing them before. Elsewise, I've begun setting up the login functionality here in Android- the first step today will be understanding and getting used to using async task, as this is a key aspect in mobile development(all these asynchronous methods make me cry).

Commit 8: Reset the old http method back because... Yeah, the new versions didn't work right. I set up the Login function correctly- Login implements the singleton pattern successfully, the XML parses through and initialises its class variables correctly... It's all working- albeit it looks awful code wise. In particular, the XML method is looking awful.

Commit 9: Begun work on the appointment functionality. I've decided to setup the classes to pass through a diary object instead of writing code in the activity of both. this should hopefully help speed, and help with code reuse(I can just write a single Controller class).

Commit 10: I've implemented the Appointment diary functionality on today and tomorrow page. It's getting there- I can pull all the data in- but my dates do not match the specified UTF layout of time. I'll get researching on that. ListView wise, the formatting isn't the "Super heading, sub heading" layout that I have for Windows and iOS. I'll have to research how best to implement that particular design setup, as while it looks fine right now... I think it would look better with a detail TextView for the title.

Commit 11: I've added the correct date format to the listview, so now it's yyyy-MM-dd T HH:mm:ss as requested. Haven't fixed up the layout yet... that will need some more time. I will probably have to setup my own layout from which to use in the listview. I'd love to not have to do that... but well, that's life.

Commit 12: Added a header to the Appointment ListView. this is just something small, but I'd like to make sure everything is CRYSTAL clear for users, as otherwise people will get confused... which isn't good. To do it, I had to make a header xml layout with a Textview inside... It means I COULD make my own views for listviews now and then- using the overloaded getView from the array adapter- just load my own... hmmm... Interesting for future applications.

Commit 12: Settings functionality foundation has been built. as Phil has yet to finish the API, I've nothing else to parse through... As such, I only check for the intErrorID and the strError. HttpClient reused. all is well with the world...
Commit 12: Moved views into a View folder for easier navigation of file hierarchy.
